rs contesting politicized seed regulations, and the application of Indigenous standards to Canadian environmental assessments. They emphasize the uncomfortable fit between the inconsistent implementation of standards in the real world and the non-negotiable criteria presupposed by external forces. The Social Life of Standards provides support for a reflexive process that involves local engagement. Ultimately, the goal should be to reach a balance between evidence-based science and the social contexts that can inform more useful and appropriate standards.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnthropologyxMethodology. 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aResearchxMethodology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aAnglaret, Xavier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCandler, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarnell, Regna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarnell, Regna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDesclaux, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscobar, Laura Gutiérrez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitting, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Janice E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Janice E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarmon, Shawn H.E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Christina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJacobs, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Jane, econtrib